The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Mumbai, Nov. 14: Gold prices touched a new high today as the price of the yellow metal rose on the overseas markets as well as there was a hectic demand from stockists in view of the wedding season. Both standard and pure gold closed at record highs of Rs 7,020 and Rs 7,055, respectively, on the bullion market. Silver also attracted a heavy demand. Gold rose in London as the dollar weakened against the euro. Gold for immediate delivery rose $2.24, or 0.5 per cent, to $470.95 an ounce. The precious metal traded at $470.50 an ounce.

 New Delhi, Nov. 14: The government has constituted a committee of secretaries to speed up the revival of public sector units, which have been cleared by the Board for Reconstruction of Public Enterprises. ?The committee has been constituted at the intervention of the cabinet secretariat,? sources said.

 New Delhi, Nov. 14: Fortis, the new owners of Escorts Heart Institute and Research Centre, today said prior consent of the Delhi Development Authority was not required for purchasing the hospital from Rajan Nanda.

 Mumbai, Nov. 14: Hindalco Industries Ltd has fixed a price of Rs 96 per share for the rights issue to raise Rs 2,500 crore, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. 

 Hong Kong, Nov. 14: ICICI Bank Ltd is teaming up with Hong Kong?s Bank of East Asia to offer services to its clients with operations in Greater China, the banks said today.




